<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-02-01T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-02-01T03:00:00-05:00" n="39" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d39">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.71 Manchuria/82: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-02-01T16:00:00+08:00">February 1, 1935—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received February 1—7:51 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>54. Department’s 2, January 4, 6 p.m. Local foreign Commissioner of Posts
                            states that parcel post and money order services between China and
                            “Manchukuo” began today.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>